04877nam a22008055i 9780231548618DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018024685  a97802315486187 a10.7312/kell189902doi  a(DE-B1597)514666  a(OCoLC)1057700606  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBL65.P7bK45 2018 4aBL65.P7 7aSCI0920002bisacsh04a201.82231 aKeller, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitical Theology of the Earth :bOur Planetary Emergency and the Struggle for a New Public /cCatherine Keller. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInsurrections: Critical Studies in Religion, Politics, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tBEGINNING -- t1. Political: Sovereign Exception or Collective Inception -- t2. Earth: Climate of Closure, Matter of Disclosure -- t3. Theology: “Unknow Better Now” -- tAPOPHATIC AFTERWORD -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmid melting glaciers, rising waters, and spreading droughts, Earth has ceased to tolerate our pretense of mastery over it. But how can we confront climate change when political crises keep exploding in the present? Noted ecotheologian and feminist philosopher of religion Catherine Keller reads the feedback loop of political and ecological depredation as secularized apocalypse. Carl Schmitt’s political theology of the sovereign exception sheds light on present ideological warfare; racial, ethnic, economic, and sexual conflict; and hubristic anthropocentrism. If the politics of exceptionalism are theological in origin, she asks, should we not enlist the world’s religious communities as part of the resistance?Keller calls for dissolving the opposition between the religious and the secular in favor of a broad planetary movement for social and ecological justice. When we are confronted by populist, authoritarian right wings founded on white male Christian supremacism, we can counter with a messianically charged, often unspoken theology of the now-moment, calling for a complex new public. Such a political theology of the earth activates the world’s entangled populations, joined in solidarity and committed to revolutionary solutions to the entwined crises of the Anthropocene.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEcologyxPolitical aspects. 0aEcologyxReligious aspects. 0aPolitical theology. 0aPublic theology. 0aReligion and politics. 7aSCIENCE / Global Warming & Climate Change.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2018 Englishz978311060424508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2018z9783110603248oZDB-23-DGF40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kell1899040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231548618423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231548618.jpg  a978-3-11-060424-5  EBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060660-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  